from any of various places called Burley, for example in Hampshire, Rutland, Shropshire, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor, stronghold’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","English: variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Bürli</b>: from a diminutive of <i>būr</i> ‘peasant, farmer’ (see   Bauer  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Burleigh","meanings":["English: variant of   Burley  ."]},{"name":"Berley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Burley  . This surname is now rare in Britain. It may also be a variant of   Birley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Beerli</b>, <b>Berli</b>, or <b>Berly</b>, and probably also of their South German cognate   Behrle   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. Compare   Barley  ."]},{"name":"Birley","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birley in Ecclesfield (Yorkshire), East or North Bierley (Yorkshire), or Birley (Derbyshire)."]},{"name":"Burlew","meanings":["Probably a variant of   Burley   1 or 2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Burley of Bromcroft was born in 1440. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Anna Mae Walking. He died in 1530, in Glamorgan, Wales, at the age of 90, and was buried i